## Windows-Specific Setup (Required Before First Build)

The happy path above works on macOS. On Windows with Gradle 9, several one-time fixes are needed.

### 1 — Install both JDK 17 and JDK 21

The build needs two JDK versions simultaneously:

- **JDK 17** — required by the React Native Gradle settings-plugin (compiles itself first)
- **JDK 21** — required by expo-modules-core, react-native-screens, react-native-safe-area-context

Android Studio ships with JBR (Java 21). You need to separately install **Eclipse Temurin JDK 17** from [adoptium.net](https://adoptium.net/).

Set `JAVA_HOME` to JDK 17 when running the build:

```powershell
$env:JAVA_HOME = "C:\Users\<you>\AppData\Local\Programs\Eclipse Adoptium\jdk-17.0.x.x-hotspot"
$env:ANDROID_HOME = "C:\Users\<you>\AppData\Local\Android\Sdk"
npx expo run:android
```

### 2 — Register both JDKs in `android/gradle.properties`

Add these lines so Gradle finds both JDKs without downloading from the internet:

```properties
org.gradle.java.installations.auto-download=false
org.gradle.java.installations.paths=C:/Users/<you>/AppData/Local/Programs/Eclipse Adoptium/jdk-17.0.x.x-hotspot,C:/Program Files/Android/Android Studio/jbr
kotlin.jvm.target.validation.mode=IGNORE
```

`IGNORE` suppresses JVM target mismatch warnings between Kotlin and Java compile tasks in third-party libraries — without it, the build fails on libraries that set these inconsistently.

### 3 — Disable the Foojay plugin in the React Native Gradle plugin

The RN Gradle plugin ships with a Foojay auto-download plugin (version 0.5.0) that references an API removed in Gradle 9. Comment it out:

**File:** `node_modules/@react-native/gradle-plugin/settings.gradle.kts`

Change:

```kotlin
plugins { id("org.gradle.toolchains.foojay-resolver-convention").version("0.8.0") }
```

To:

```kotlin
// Foojay disabled — JDK 17 and 21 provided via org.gradle.java.installations.paths
// plugins { id("org.gradle.toolchains.foojay-resolver-convention").version("0.8.0") }
```

> ⚠️ This file is inside `node_modules` — the change will be lost after `npm install`. If you re-run install, re-apply this comment. Consider adding a `postinstall` script to automate it.

### 4 — Target your device explicitly

Verify your phone is connected and authorized:

```powershell
adb devices
```

Output should show `device` (not `unauthorized`). If it shows `unauthorized`, tap **Allow** on the phone screen.

Then set your device serial before building so the emulator isn't selected instead:

```powershell
$env:ANDROID_SERIAL = "your-device-serial-from-adb-devices"
```

